text:
It‚Äôs ironic that this song reflects a lot of the unreal expectations that people have about trading their own for a perfect life. Whether that‚Äôs like a scenario in a game or movie. And I think it‚Äôs common for people to dream of stuff mentioned in the song, like being able to master a skill, or achieve a good physic with minimal effort. It ties up with the theme of escaping reality , the thought of it is depressing considering this is true for many people.

Near the end, in fact throughout the whole song. It reflects a miserable mindset of living. One that wants to sacrifice all the safety from this world just to be rebirthed into a world full of adventure. Caused by unreal standards created by media, As well as things we don‚Äôt have. Sometimes something‚Äôs can‚Äôt be achieved, not all of us can live that perfect life that we desire. Things that we want, but don‚Äôt have.

I‚Äôm not sure if im making sense  rn with everything I said so far. But basically, this song reflects many issues with the current/new generation including depression, desires, unreal expectations etc. At one point of our lives we all wanted to escape this world, well I think, I don‚Äôt suppose there‚Äôs a person that hasn‚Äôt. But all we could do is make the most of it, it‚Äôs rather negative to have petty thoughts like these that take up little space of our existence to ruin a part of our lives.

I've been getting a bit of the seven deadly sins vibe with these dyes iwasaki collab songs, with Marine's song representing Lust, this one being Sloth and Chloe's being Envy, the non-hololive ones are a bit harder to pin down, but I'd say Pmaru's song (dead or like) is possibly pride (due to the obsession with one's own image and being "liked"), Toko's is Greed, (since it's both about taking money from others to provide "services" but also punishing them on repeat visits, essentially punishing them for getting greedy and wanting more) while Kurumi's is gluttony. (this one kinda breaks down my theory because it's not as direct as the others, but the food imagery and sense of being high, both with the contrast of the space visuals and and vibrant colours against dark and gloomy settings implies a relation to substance addiction, but the lyrics don't REALLY support that so I'm kinda stretching it a bit)

if my theory is correct, then the next vtuber collab song will be related to anger or wrath.

text:
The start of the video is a woman living with her parents, shut in, broke, addicted to video games and alcohol, and just want life in "easy mode.'" 
By the second verse, she's starting to consider her future but still stuck in the rut, still wants that easy mode. 
Finally she realizes that nothing will change by sitting around and praying for it. Her perspective changed to "hard mode," taking charge and reversing fate. 
As she bids goodbye to the useless life, cleans up herself, her room, got a job and walks out into the world.

It hits kinda close to home as I've been through this arc. It's got a message that I think a lot of people can use.
